Phase.description:
The deployment process for an Air Force reservist typically involves several phases:

Notification: Reservists are notified of their deployment through official channels. This notification includes details about the deployment, such as duration, location, and mission.
Pre-deployment Preparation: Reservists undergo pre-deployment training and preparation to ensure they are ready for their mission. This may include specialized training related to their role, as well as medical and administrative tasks.
Mobilization: Reservists are mobilized, which involves reporting to their designated mobilization station or unit. During this phase, final administrative and logistical preparations are made before departure.
Deployment: Reservists are deployed to their assigned location. This phase involves traveling to the deployment location and transitioning into the operational environment.
Mission Execution: Reservists carry out their assigned mission tasks in accordance with operational requirements. This may involve a variety of duties depending on the nature of the deployment, such as combat operations, support functions, or humanitarian assistance.
Reintegration: After the deployment is completed, reservists go through a reintegration process to transition back to civilian life. This may involve debriefings, medical evaluations, and support services to help them readjust to life at home.
Throughout each phase, reservists receive support from their unit, as well as access to resources and assistance to ensure a successful deployment experience.

Training Status Code - TNG_STATUS Code - used to identify members in upgrade training. Completion changes their skill level in their AFSC. Training Status Code R: This often indicates a member is in "Refresher Training." This could involve refreshing skills or knowledge in a particular area.

Training Status Code B: This typically represents "Basic Training." It indicates that the member is undergoing initial training to become proficient in their Air Force duties.

Training Status Code C: This may stand for "Continuous Training." It could indicate ongoing training that is required to maintain proficiency or to stay up-to-date with changes in procedures or technology.

Training Status Code K: This could represent "Upgrade Training." It suggests that the member is undergoing training to advance to a higher skill level or position within the Air Force.

Training Status Code P: This might denote "Special Training." It could indicate training for specialized tasks or roles within the Air Force.

Training Status Code G: This could represent "Graduate Training." It indicates that the member has completed a particular training program successfully.
